Support for individual Die/Interposer/Package or merging all components together.


Yes, the logical relationship is as follows: 1) PLOC is provided by RedhawkSC. 2) When the slave imports PLOC, the number of PLOC pins may exceed the number of SIwave Die Component Pins. These excess PLOC pins are what we refer to as "float" pins in this defect. 3) After the CPA solution is completed, the back-annotation information is provided to the PLOC supplied by RedhawkSC and packaged along with the Netlist for use by RHSC.
When back-annotating PLOC, we do not delete the original PLOC information; instead, we merely establish a correspondence between the CPA Netlist Nodes and the chip nodes in the original PLOC. Consequently, we need to handle the extra pins in PLOC, categorizing them as either "float" or "connected to a voltage." Currently, SIwave defaults to "connected to a voltage," which can lead to potential issues. In reality, we prefer the default to be "float."


 When we choose not to include certain nets in the analysis, we should consider the pins on these nets as non-existent for the purpose of the analysis. However, since these pins still exist in the PLOC, we need to treat them as "Unconnected die pins" and have them (nets) appear in the "Unconnected die pins" list.
 
 These two issues are somewhat related, and I believe they can be addressed together as a single enhancement.
 
 We hope that the behavior of SIwave-CPA can be as consistent as possible with that of Redhawk-CPA, as this will help reduce user confusion. 
 If possible that synchronizing with the SCBU RD Teams regarding the recently mentioned CPA issues to see if we can learn from each other's experiences. In fact, it was after our EBU AE Teams cross-checked with the SCBU AE Teams that we discovered the differences in settings between our two tools.
 
 
 Recently, there have been numerous CPA issues raised in our China region, mainly due to deeper customer requirements encountered in several 3DIC Package projects. As the number of 3DIC Package projects grows, these demands have become increasingly urgent. In fact, both we and CNDS have received similar requests. Currently, customers are oscillating between Ansys and CNDS tools, and once their make choice, it will be difficult for either of Ansys and CNDS to sway them, which could also influence the choices of other customers with similar needs. 
 If we hope for the AE Teams to provide more information on customer requirements, competitive intelligence, or technical details and suggestions, I think we could organize a meeting. In fact, we've already had a brief meeting with Shankar,We have also invited Zhonghai to participate in customer project meetings, and I believe we could engage in even more in-depth technical exchanges.